'''Kenneth Stanley Inglis''', {{postnominals|country=AUS|size=100|sep=,|AO|FASSA}} (7 October 1929 – 1 December 2017) was an Australian historian.

Inglis completed his [[Master's degree]] at the [[University of Melbourne]] and his [[Doctor of Philosophy|doctorate]] at the [[University of Oxford]]. In 1956 he was appointed as a lecturer to the [[University of Adelaide]]. He subsequently became Professor of History at the [[Australian National University]], and the [[University of Papua New Guinea]].<ref name="UniAdelMS">{{cite web | year=2006 | url=http://www.adelaide.edu.au/library/special/inglis.html | title=Kenneth Stanley Inglis, 1929– Lectures in history, University of Adelaide 1956–59 MSS 0067 | work=University Library: Access to Manuscript Collections | publisher=University of Adelaide | accessdate=2008-03-19 | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://archive.is/20070813125531/http://www.adelaide.edu.au/library/special/inglis.html | archivedate=13 August 2007 | df=dmy-all }} </ref>

Inglis has written extensively on the [[Anzac]] tradition, the [[Max Stuart|Stuart Case]], [[war memorial]]s, and the [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]].<ref name = "UniAdelMS"/> In 2008 he joined the Faculty of Arts at Monash University, Melbourne, as an Adjunct Professor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://artsonline.monash.edu.au/history-studies/associate-staff-profiles/|title=Associate Staff Profiles|date=2014-10-17|website=History|language=en-US|access-date=2016-05-13}}</ref>

Inglis died, aged 88, on 1 December 2017.<ref name="deathref">{{cite news|title=Historian Ken Inglis dies, aged 88|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/arts/books/historian-ken-inglis-dies-aged-88/news-story/1913787102a2543bf8f601596a7fb1a5|accessdate=4 December 2017|work=The Australian|date=3 December 2017}}</ref>

==Early life and education==
Inglis was born in the [[Melbourne]] suburb of [[Ivanhoe, Victoria]], on 7 October 1929, the son of Stan and Rene Inglis. He was educated at Tyler Street Public School, Northcote Boys' Hight School and [[Melbourne High School]], before going to study at the [[University of Melbourne]]. Inglis participated in the Student Christian Movement and amateur dramatics during his studies, and worked as a tutor at [[Ormond College]]. After graduating with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] with first class honours in History and English, he read for a [[Master of Arts]] at Melbourne. Inglis' thesis, which was a history of the [[Royal Melbourne Hospital]], was later revised and published as his first book, ''Hospital and Community'' ([[Melbourne University Press]], 1958).<ref name="AHS">{{cite journal|last1=Frances|first1=Raelene|last2=Scates|first2=Bruce|date=2018|title=Kenneth Stanley Inglis AO (1929–2017)|journal=Australian Historical Studies|volume=49|issue=3|pages=410–412|doi=10.1080/1031461X.2018.1493961}}</ref><ref name="SMH">{{cite news|last=Stephens|first=Tony|title=Ken Inglis, Anzac Historian, Foremost a Storyteller|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/ken-inglis-anzac-historian-foremost-a-storyteller-20180116-h0iun3.html|newspaper=[[Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=16 January 2018|accessdate=14 August 2018}}</ref>

