{{Chinese name|[[Zuo (surname)|Zuo]]}}
{{chinese
|c={{linktext|左|丘|明}}
|p=Zuǒ Qiūmíng<br>Zuǒqiū Míng
|w=Tso Ch&lsquo;iu-ming<br>Tso-ch&lsquo;iu Ming
}}

'''Zuo Qiuming''', '''Zuoqiu Ming''' or '''Qiu Ming'''{{efn|In surviving sources, it is uncertain whether his [[Chinese name|surname]] was [[Zuo (surname)|Zuo]] or Zuoqiu. An alternate viewpoint is that his name is Qiu Ming; "Zuo" refers to his official post of ''zuoshi'', which has remained in his family for some generations.}} (556 BC-451 BC)<ref> ''Confucius and [[Lao Zhu]] Their Differing Social Foundations and Cultures'' Sino-Platonic Papers 211 2011</ref> was a Chinese writer and contemporary of [[Confucius]] who lived in the [[Lu (state)|State of Lu]] during the [[Spring and Autumn period]] of ancient China. 

The influential ''[[Zuozhuan]]'' (''Commentary of Zuo'') is traditionally attributed to him.<ref>{{cite book|title=Rhetoric in ancient China, fifth to third century, B.C.: a comparison with classical Greek rhetoric|author=Xing Lu|publisher=[[University of South Carolina Press]]|year=1998|page=107|isbn=1-57003-216-5}}</ref> He is also possibly a contributor to ''[[Guoyu (book)|Guoyu]]''. One tradition, according to the ''[[Records of the Grand Historian]]'', holds that he was blind (cf. [[Homer]]).

Zuo is noted in the ''[[Analects]]'' as a paragon of virtue to Confucius.{{efn|{{lang-zh|子曰：「巧言、令色、足恭，左丘明恥之，丘亦恥之。匿怨而友其人，左丘明恥之，丘亦恥之。}} "The Master said, "Fine words, an insinuating appearance, and excessive respect - Zuo Qiuming was ashamed of them. I also am ashamed of them. To conceal resentment against a person, and appear friendly with him - Zuo Qiuming was ashamed of such conduct. I also am ashamed of it."<ref>''Confucian Analects'', translated by [[James Legge]] in Vol. I of ''The Chinese Classics''.</ref>}}

